15
00:00:41,090 --> 00:00:44,960
history people thought
qualitatively, not

16
00:00:44,960 --> 00:00:46,900
quantitatively.

17
00:00:46,900 --> 00:00:49,020
They didn't know what
statistics were.

18
00:00:49,020 --> 00:00:52,590
They must have had some
intuitive sense, for example,

19
00:00:52,590 --> 00:00:56,030
that if you're old, you're
more likely to have bad

20
00:00:56,030 --> 00:00:58,000
hearing than if you're young.

21
00:00:58,000 --> 00:01:00,040
If you're old you're
more likely to die

22
00:01:00,040 --> 00:01:00,940
than if you're young.

23
00:01:00,940 --> 00:01:02,500
Things like that.

24
00:01:02,500 --> 00:01:06,890
But they were just anecdotes,
and they had no careful way to

25
00:01:06,890 --> 00:01:10,170
go from statements about
individuals to statements

26
00:01:10,170 --> 00:01:14,050
about populations
or expectations.

27
00:01:14,050 --> 00:01:18,550
This changed in about the middle
of the 17th century,

28
00:01:18,550 --> 00:01:22,970
changed fairly dramatically,
when an Englishman named John

29
00:01:22,970 --> 00:01:26,380
Graunt published something
called The Natural and

30
00:01:26,380 --> 00:01:32,110
Political Observations Made Upon
the Bills of Mortality.

31
00:01:32,110 --> 00:01:36,990
This was the first work in
recorded history that actually

32
00:01:36,990 --> 00:01:39,050
used statistics.

33
00:01:39,050 --> 00:01:42,540
And what he did is he looked
at the fairly comprehensive

34
00:01:42,540 --> 00:01:47,180
statistics of when people died
in the city of London.

35
00:01:47,180 --> 00:01:51,070
And from that, attempted to
produce a model that could be

36
00:01:51,070 --> 00:01:55,400
used to predict the spread
of the plague.

37
00:01:55,400 --> 00:01:58,800
And it turns out, he was
pretty good at it.

38
00:01:58,800 --> 00:02:01,530
And that just changed the way
people started to think.

39
00:02:01,530 --> 00:02:06,910
And since that time, people have
used statistics both to

40
00:02:06,910 --> 00:02:09,304
inform and, unfortunately,
to mislead.

41
00:02:09,304 --> 00:02:12,400

42
00:02:12,400 --> 00:02:17,840
Some have willfully used
statistics to mislead, others

43
00:02:17,840 --> 00:02:20,430
have merely been incompetent.

44
00:02:20,430 --> 00:02:23,760
And that gets me to what I
want to talk about today,

45
00:02:23,760 --> 00:02:25,750
which is statistics.

46
00:02:25,750 --> 00:02:29,060

47
00:02:29,060 --> 00:02:32,070
This is often attributed to Mark
Twain but, in fact, he

48
00:02:32,070 --> 00:02:35,750
copied it from Benjamin
Disraeli, who said, "There are

49
00:02:35,750 --> 00:02:43,760
three kinds of lies: lies,
damned lies, and statistics."

50
00:02:43,760 --> 00:02:49,840
And there is, unfortunately,
a lot of truth in that.

51
00:02:49,840 --> 00:02:53,080
More recently, in the '50s
Darrell Huff wrote a wonderful

52
00:02:53,080 --> 00:02:58,030
book, I recommend it, called
How to Lie with Statistics.

53
00:02:58,030 --> 00:03:01,290
Now here's a quote from the
book, "If you can't prove what

54
00:03:01,290 --> 00:03:05,540
you want to prove, demonstrate
something else and pretend

55
00:03:05,540 --> 00:03:07,360
that they're the same thing.

56
00:03:07,360 --> 00:03:10,530
In the daze that follows the
collision of statistics with

57
00:03:10,530 --> 00:03:15,270
the human mind, hardly anyone
will notice the difference."

58
00:03:15,270 --> 00:03:19,340
Alas, that seems to be true.

59
00:03:19,340 --> 00:03:24,900
So what I want to do today is
talk about a few ways in which

60
00:03:24,900 --> 00:03:29,230
one can be fooled into drawing
inappropriate conclusions from

61
00:03:29,230 --> 00:03:31,610
statistical data.

62
00:03:31,610 --> 00:03:34,100
Now I trust that you
will use this

63
00:03:34,100 --> 00:03:36,750
information only for good.

64
00:03:36,750 --> 00:03:42,170
And it will make you a better
consumer and purveyor of data

65
00:03:42,170 --> 00:03:46,980
rather than a better liar,
but that's up to you.

66
00:03:46,980 --> 00:03:47,810
All right.

67
00:03:47,810 --> 00:03:52,430
So let's start with the
first way out thing I

68
00:03:52,430 --> 00:03:54,540
want to talk about.

69
00:03:54,540 --> 00:03:59,150
And it's important to always
remember that no matter how

70
00:03:59,150 --> 00:04:08,690
good your statistics are,
statistical measures don't

71
00:04:08,690 --> 00:04:09,940
tell the whole story.

72
00:04:09,940 --> 00:04:12,310

73
00:04:12,310 --> 00:04:15,575
We've seen examples of this
already earlier in the term.

74
00:04:15,575 --> 00:04:19,480

75
00:04:19,480 --> 00:04:22,290
There are an enormous set of
statistics that can be

76
00:04:22,290 --> 00:04:24,670
extracted from a data set.

77
00:04:24,670 --> 00:04:28,480
And by carefully picking and
choosing among them, it's

78
00:04:28,480 --> 00:04:33,450
possible to convey almost any
impression you want about the

79
00:04:33,450 --> 00:04:35,590
same data set.

80
00:04:35,590 --> 00:04:40,250
The best antidote, of course, is
to look at the data itself.

81
00:04:40,250 --> 00:04:46,320
In 1973, the statistician John
Anscombe published a paper

82
00:04:46,320 --> 00:04:50,050
with this set of data.

83
00:04:50,050 --> 00:04:56,760
Four different examples where
he gave values for x and y,

84
00:04:56,760 --> 00:04:59,570
nothing very sophisticated.

85
00:04:59,570 --> 00:05:06,150
The interesting thing is that
in many ways, the statistics

86
00:05:06,150 --> 00:05:09,085
for these four data sets
are very similar.

87
00:05:09,085 --> 00:05:11,730

88
00:05:11,730 --> 00:05:18,980
They have the same mean, the
same median, the same variance

89
00:05:18,980 --> 00:05:24,020
for x and y both, the same
correlation between x and y.

90
00:05:24,020 --> 00:05:28,520
And even if we use linear
regression to get a fit, we

91
00:05:28,520 --> 00:05:30,210
get very similar things.

92
00:05:30,210 --> 00:05:32,070
So let's look at it.

93
00:05:32,070 --> 00:05:36,130
I actually wrote some
code to do that.

94
00:05:36,130 --> 00:05:42,520
So this just reads in the data
set that we just had up, and

95
00:05:42,520 --> 00:05:45,810
